>
  <article>
    <div class="article-header">
      <h1>Cannabis Taxation & 280E</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Understanding cannabis business taxation in Maine</p>
    </div>

    <section class="fact-box">
      <h2>Maine Cannabis Tax at a Glance</h2>
      <table aria-label="Maine cannabis 280E tax requirements and rates">
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Federal Law</strong></td><td>IRC 280E - No normal business deductions</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Only Deductible</strong></td><td>Cost of Goods Sold (COGS)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Maine Sales Tax</strong></td><td>10% on adult-use cannabis</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Maine Excise Tax</strong></td><td>Per-pound fees (verify current rates with OCP)</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Maine Income Tax</strong></td><td>Standard deductions allowed - unlike federal</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Key Advantage</strong></td><td>Maine allows normal state deductions</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Overview</h2>
      <p>Here's the problem: cannabis is still illegal at the federal level, which means standard tax deductions don't apply to cannabis businesses. IRC Section <a href="https://www.irs.gov/pub/irs-drop/rr-09-14.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">280E</a> (<strong>26 U.S.C.  280E</strong>) blocks you from writing off rent, marketing, salaries, and most other things normal businesses take for granted. This drives effective tax rates way higher than you'd expect.</p>
      <p>This isn't optional knowledge. If you don't plan for 280E from day one, it will catch you off guard when you're filing. The good news: it can be managed, and Maine's state-level deductions help.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="The Short Version" type="tip">
      280E is a pain, but it's manageable. You won't pay 70-90% of your profits in taxes - that number gets better when you maximize COGS and structure things right. Work with a cannabis-specific CPA from the start, not after your first filing.
    </Callout>

    <section>
      <h2>Section 280E Definition Explained</h2>
      <p>Section 280E was originally enacted to prevent drug traffickers from deducting business expenses. Because cannabis remains illegal at the federal level, cannabis businesses-even those fully compliant with state law-are subject to this provision.</p>
      
      <h3>What 280E Actually Means for Your Business:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>No normal deductions</strong> - rent, utilities, marketing, most salaries. Gone.</li>
        <li><strong>Only COGS is deductible</strong> - what you paid for the product you sold. That's it.</li>
        <li><strong>Effective tax rate is higher</strong> - don't believe the "70-90%" headlines. With good COGS management, you're usually looking at 40-60% effective rates in practice.</li>
        <li><strong>Applies to everyone</strong> - cultivation, manufacturing, retail, medical caregivers. If you touch cannabis, 280E applies.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Hidden Challenge: The All-or-Nothing Trap</h3>
      <p>Watch out for this one: 280E applies to your entire business if any part of it touches cannabis. If you own a coffee shop and a dispensary under the same LLC, the IRS can argue 280E applies to the coffee shop too. <strong>Keep separate businesses under separate legal entities.</strong></p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Cost of Goods Sold (COGS): Your Only Real Deduction</h2>
      <p>When 280E kills your deductions, COGS is what you have left. In a dispensary, this is basically what you paid for your inventory - the flower, concentrates, edibles on your shelves. If you bought it for $1,500/lb and sold it for $3,000/lb, your taxable income is $1,500/lb. That's your COGS lifeline.</p>
      
      <h3>Vertical Integration Changes the Math</h3>
      <p>If you own cultivation too, you can often push more costs into COGS - labor, power, nutrients - because those are "production" expenses. A dispensary with its own grow can legally lower its taxable income more than a store that just buys from a cultivator. This is why most serious Maine operators eventually move toward vertical integration. <a href="/guides/maine-cannabis-cultivation-guide/">See our Cultivation Guide for details on Tier licensing.</a></p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Maine State Taxes: The Good News</h2>
      <p>Here's the split to understand: Maine is not the IRS. On your Maine state return, you can deduct normal business expenses. This makes a real difference - your state tax burden is closer to a normal business.</p>
      
      <h3>What Maine Collects (per M.R.S. Title 28-B):</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Sales Tax:</strong> 10% on adult-use cannabis sales (this is separate from the excise tax)</li>
        <li><strong>Excise Tax:</strong> Per-pound fee - $335 per pound of flower, different rates for other product types</li>
        <li><strong>Income Tax:</strong> Maine corporate rates apply, and you can take normal deductions here</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Local X-Factor: Maine's State Tax Deduction Advantage</h2>
      <p><strong>What sets Maine apart from most other states:</strong> Unlike the federal government, Maine allows cannabis businesses to take <em>normal</em> business deductions on your Maine state tax return. This includes rent, payroll, marketing, and operating expenses - the same deductions any Maine business takes.</p>
      <p><strong>The practical impact:</strong> If your dispensary has $500K in revenue and $300K in expenses (rent, staff, marketing), you pay Maine state tax only on the $200K profit - not the full $500K. In most other cannabis states, you'd pay tax on $500K at the federal level, then get crushed by 280E eliminating your $300K deductions.</p>
      <p><strong>Under M.R.S. Title 28-B  301</strong>, Maine has explicitly separated its cannabis income tax framework from federal 280E treatment, giving Maine operators a meaningful edge in net profitability compared to operators in states without similar provisions.</p>
      <Callout title="The Bottom Line" type="passion">
        Maine's state tax structure doesn't fix 280E - but it meaningfully reduces your total tax burden. Factor this into your business plan projections.
      </Callout>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>How to Actually Reduce Your 280E Burden</h2>
      <p>Here's what's working for Maine operators who stay profitable:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Track Every Gram</strong> - Your POS needs to match Metrc exactly. Use <a href="/guides/maine-dispensary-pos/">systems designed for cannabis</a>, not generic retail software.</li>
        <li><strong>Separate Entities</strong> - Keep your "Management Company" (where you pay yourself, do marketing, etc.) separate from your Licensed Entity. This isolates non-cannabis expenses from 280E exposure.</li>
        <li><strong>Maximize COGS</strong> - Work with a cannabis CPA to attribute every legitimate cost to production. This isn't cheating - it's making sure you're not overpaying.</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Common Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq-list">
        <h3>Can I deduct my General Manager's salary?</h3>
        <p>Usually no - administrative salaries aren't deductible under 280E. But if your GM spends time on inventory tasks (receiving shipments, audits, Metrc entry), that portion can count toward COGS. Document their time.</p>

        <h3>Do 280E rules apply to Medical Caregivers?</h3>
        <p>Yes. Any business trafficking in a Schedule I or II substance falls under 280E - adult-use stores and medical caregivers alike.</p>

        <h3>What happens if I get audited?</h3>
        <p>IRS audits in cannabis are thorough. They'll pull your Metrc data and compare it to your financial records. If your inventory numbers don't match your sales reporting, that's the first thing they'll scrutinize.</p>

        <h3>Will rescheduling to Schedule III fix 280E?</h3>
        <p>Yes - and it's closer than it's ever been. If cannabis moves to Schedule III, 280E disappears and your net profit could jump 30-50% overnight. Until that actually happens, plan as if 280E is permanent.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="further-reading">
      <h2>Further Reading & Authority Resources</h2>
